t 1297–":"about 1297–Deceased","1295–Male":"1295–Deceased","1325–Female":"1325–Deceased","1297–Female":"1297–Deceased","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","about 1325":"about 1325","1453":"1453","1297":"1297","1295":"1295","about 1297":"about 1297","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Gensing, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gensing","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German:","habitational name, possibly from Lenzing in Austria.","pet form of the personal name <i>Laurentius</i> (see   Lawrence  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Lawrence","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Lorens</i>, <i>Laurence</i>, from Latin <i>Laurentius</i> ‘man from <i>Laurentum</i>’, a place in Italy probably named from its laurels or bay trees. The name was borne by a Christian saint who was martyred at Rome in the 3rd century  AD ; he enjoyed a considerable cult throughout Europe, with consequent popularity of the personal name (French <i>Laurent</i>, Italian, Spanish <i>Lorenzo</i>, Catalan <i>Llorenç</i>, Portuguese <i>Lourenço</i>, German <i>Laurenz</i>, Polish <i>Wawrzyniec</i>, etc.). In Britain this is a common name from the 12th century, with pet forms such as   Law  ,   Low  ,   Lawrie  ,   Laurie  ,   Larry  ,   Larkin  , all of which are represented in surnames. There was also a feminine form <i>Laurencia</i> which may have given rise to the English surname. The surname is also borne by Jews among whom it is presumably an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Ashkenazic surnames. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages, e.g. German   Lorenz  , and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Slovenian <b>Lavrenčič</b> and <b>Lovrenčič</b> (patronymics from <i>Lavrencij</i> and <i>Lovrenc</i>, equivalents of <i>Lawrence</i>), Polish   Wawrzyniak  . Compare   Larrance  ,   Laurence  ,   Lawerence  ,   Lieurance  , and   Lowrance  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":18,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":31,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":40,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Robert de Gensing was born about 1297, in Sussex, England. She had at least 1 daughter with Robert de Gensing."},"et":{"about 1297–":"umbes 1297–Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1297–Female":"1297–Surnud","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","about 1325":"umbes 1325","1453":"1453","1297":"1297","1295":"1295","about 1297":"umbes 1297","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Gensing, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fi":{"about 1297–":"noin 1297–Kuollut","1295–Male":"1295–Kuollut","1325–Female":"1325–Kuollut","1297–Female":"1297–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","about 1325":"noin 1325","1453":"1453","1297":"1297","1295":"1295","about 1297":"noin 1297","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Gensing, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fr":{"about 1297–":"environ 1297–Décédée","1295–Male":"1295–Décédé","1325–Female":"1325–Décédée","1297–Female":"1297–Décédée","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","about 1325":"environ 1325","1453":"1453","1297":"1297","1295":"1295","about 1297":"environ 1297","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Gensi